WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.640
My name is Tom Mock. I'm the Workbench product manager here at Posit. I've kind of built my

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:17.719
career thinking about the developer experience, so worked in the Cordo team as a product manager

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:22.400
thinking about how we integrate R and Python together for notebooks and extending them,

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:27.160
and now I'm focusing almost all of my time on the developer experience for Workbench and

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.480
integrating R and Python there for data scientists and their daily work.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:39.880
Posit team is kind of our crown jewel or a bundle of all of our professional products. So you have

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:44.160
three kind of parts to this that all are complementary, but also isolated products.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:47.880
So maybe you only need one or maybe you need all of them, but y'all get to make that choice

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:53.320
in terms of flexibility. So Posit Workbench is your workbench where your data scientists,

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:58.919
your data analysts, the people who write R, Python, SQL, they get their work done. We provide

00:00:58.919 --> 00:01:04.080
an authenticated workspace with best-in-class enterprise, single sign-on, and SAML and the

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:08.760
things you would expect, but we also provide multiple environments for those data scientists

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:13.519
to get their work done. So of course you have RStudio for people who are maybe doing a mix of

00:01:13.519 --> 00:01:19.239
R and Python. You can execute code there. We've also got more traditional and kind of expected

00:01:19.279 --> 00:01:23.480
pure Python environments. So we have access to JupyterLab as well as classic Jupyter notebooks.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:29.080
And then VS Code, which is this very open-ended and flexible integrated development environment,

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:36.239
is also available on Workbench. Posit Workbench provides an IDE, VS Code, Jupyter, JupyterLab,

00:01:36.239 --> 00:01:42.000
RStudio, some place to do that work. Eventually though, you want to get it off of that environment

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.959
where you both track how it's performing there, but also how it affect part of your business or

00:01:46.959 --> 00:01:51.879
integrate with other parts of your company. So as soon as you're ready to get it off of your local

00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:57.639
environment, you can deploy it to Connect. You can have a command line where you kind of write

00:01:57.639 --> 00:02:02.160
it up the application and then you deploy it with authentication into Connect, but you can also

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:06.720
integrate it into version control or kind of continuous integration and continuous deployment

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:12.399
where it goes into something like GitHub or GitLab and then gets pulled automatically into Connect.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:17.440
The last part of it would be Posit Package Manager. Again, with open source, you have all

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:22.479
this flexibility, but with flexibility can sometimes come complexity. Posit Package Manager is really

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:27.199
this backbone behind all of our other tooling. Ultimately, to do open source data science,

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:32.399
you need open source data science libraries and packages. So Posit Package Manager allows you to

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:37.039
host both your own Python packages, so you can create your own wheels, upload them to Posit

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:42.960
Package Manager and have them stored there, as well as grab subsets or all of PyPI and kind of

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:47.520
the other open source packages that the whole community is working on. So that really takes

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:52.960
away a lot of the headache of having to manage more complex structures. You don't have to use

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:58.240
Docker. You don't have to use tools like Conda. You don't have to manage all these system dependencies.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:03.679
You're really focused on purely writing Python code and indicating what are the libraries or

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:09.839
packages that provide the functionality I want. So Python at its most simple is part of what Posit

00:03:09.839 --> 00:03:18.880
team provides for you. Posit historically has been known for the RStudio IDE. That's kind of our

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:24.880
crown jewel of developer experience for our users. We've done a lot of investments for Python users

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:30.399
as well, however, and so we have Cordo, we have Vetiver, we have all these open source tools

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:36.080
that really try to make data science seamless for Python users. So part of our investment in open

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:40.800
source is that we are both doing it ourselves and integrating with others. So if you think about

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.440
Posit the company, about half of our company is engineering and about half of our engineers

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:51.600
are working purely on open source. So we're making huge investments in terms of people hours

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:57.679
in improving and maintaining professionally supported open source data science packages.

00:03:57.679 --> 00:04:03.199
Over time you might have shifts in how you're developing your tooling or writing your models

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:08.240
and we want to kind of future-proof the platform so that as new framers come out we're adding those

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:11.919
in and making sure that they're supported and we're testing against them as well as

00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:15.119
allowing them to be deployed into things on production.

